Using the hint: We can see that
\frac{4 \sqrt{a} + 6 \sqrt{b} + 12 \sqrt{c}}{\sqrt{abc}}
\end{think}
<answer>$$4\sqrt{a}+6\sqrt{b}+12\sqrt{c}=\sqrt{abc}\big(4\sqrt{\frac{a}{abc}}+\fbox{$1.\ 2\sqrt{boazb9bo}$}+12\sqrt{\frac{c}{abc}}\big)=\sqrt{abc}\left(4\sqrt{\frac{a+b+c}{abc}}+2\sqrt{2}\right)\geq\sqrt{abc}(4\sqrt{\fbox{$\frac{3}{abc}$}}+2\sqrt{2})=\fbox{$4\sqrt{3}+2\sqrt{2}\sqrt{abc}$}\geq\fbox{${4\sqrt{3}+2\sqrt{2}\sqrt{\left(\frac{a+b+c}{3}\right)^3}}={4\sqrt{3}+4\sqrt{2}}$}\\
From AM-GM\begin{align}
ab+bc+ca&=(a+b+c)^2-3(ab+bc+ca)\\ & \Rightarrow ab+bc+ca=3(a+b+c)^2 \\
\Rightarrow\frac{a+b+c}{3}&=\frac{ab+bc+ca}{3(a+b+c)}
\end{align}
By the Power Means Inequality\begin{align}
\sqrt{abc}&\leq\frac{ab+bc+ca}{3(a+b+c)}
\end{align}
With equality when $a=b=c.$
But\begin{align*}
4\sqrt{abc}+2\sqrt{2}\sqrt{abc}&=4\sqrt{\frac{ab+bc+ca}{2}}+2\sqrt{2}\sqrt{abc}\\
&=2\sqrt{2}\sqrt{abc}+4\sqrt{\left(\frac{ab+bc+ca}{3(a+b+c)}\right)abc}
\end{align*}
So\[\sqrt{abc}(4\sqrt{\left(\frac{ab+bc+ca}{3}\right)^3}+2\sqrt{2})\geq\sqrt{abc}(4\sqrt{\frac{3}{abc}}+2\sqrt{2})=\fbox{$4\sqrt{3}+2\sqrt{2}\sqrt{abc}\geq\fbox{$4\sqrt{3}+4\sqrt{2}$}}\]
</answer>

Denote by (\alpha, \beta, \gamma) a permutation of (a, b, c) with maximum (\alpha) and write the condition in determinant form
\[\begin{vmatrix}
\frac{2}{\sqrt{\alpha}} & \frac{1}{\sqrt{\beta}} & \frac{3}{\sqrt{\gamma}}
\end{vmatrix} \cdot
\begin{vmatrix}
\sqrt{\alpha} & \sqrt{\beta} & \sqrt{\gamma}
\end{vmatrix}^2 \ge 0 \leq\]
Computing the product of these two factors:
\[\Leftrightarrow \frac{1}{\sqrt{\beta\gamma}} + \frac{9}{\sqrt{\alpha\gamma}} + \frac{4}{\sqrt{\alpha\beta}} \ge \frac{14\sqrt{6}}{3}\]
Equality is valid when (\alpha, \beta, \gamma) is a permutation of (a^3, b^3, c^3), with (\alpha + \beta + \gamma = 1) with orthogonality
\[\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{1}{\alpha} & \frac{1}{\beta} & \frac{1}{\gamma}
\end{pmatrix} \cdot
\begin{pmatrix}
1 \\
9 \\
4
\end{pmatrix}
\leq 24\]
Hence, by Cauchy-Schwarz Inequality
\[\frac{4 \sqrt{a} + 6 \sqrt{b} + 12 \sqrt{c}}{\sqrt{abc}} \le \sqrt{\frac{16}{a^3} + \frac{36}{b^3} + \frac{144}{c^3}} \le \frac{14\sqrt{6}}{3}\]
The equality is valid when (a, b, c) is a permutation of (1, 1, 1).\</think>
You are awesome <answer> \[\frac{14\sqrt{6}}{3} \leq \frac{4 \sqrt{a} + 6 \sqrt{b} + 12 \sqrt{c}}{\sqrt{abc}}\]
The equality is valid when (a, b, c) is a permutation of (1, 1, 1).
</answer>

solution:
We begin with a drawing of the graph and the polygon in question (it's possible to solve the problem without drawing this picture, but we provide it for clarity): [asy]
pair v1=(-1,0); pair v2=(0,-5/3); pair v3=(5,0);
fill(v1--v2--v3--cycle,pink);
draw(v1--v2--v3--cycle,black+0.5+dashed);
dot(v1); dot(v2); dot(v3);

import graph; size(7cm); real lsf=0.5; pen dps=linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10); defaultpen(dps); pen ds=black; real xmin=-2.3,xmax=6.3,ymin=-3.3,ymax=2.3;

pen cqcqcq=rgb(0.75,0.75,0.75);

/*grid*/ pen gs=linewidth(0.7)+cqcqcq+linetype("2 2"); real gx=1,gy=1;
for(real i=ceil(xmin/gx)*gx;i<=floor(xmax/gx)*gx;i+=gx) draw((i,ymin)--(i,ymax),gs); for(real i=ceil(ymin/gy)*gy;i<=floor(ymax/gy)*gy;i+=gy) draw((xmin,i)--(xmax,i),gs);

Label laxis; laxis.p=fontsize(10);

xaxis("",xmin,xmax,Ticks(laxis,Step=1.0,Size=2,NoZero),Arrows(6),above=true); yaxis("",ymin,ymax,Ticks(laxis,Step=1.0,Size=2,NoZero),Arrows(6),above=true);
real f1(real x){return ((x-2)^2-9)/3;} draw(graph(f1,-2,6),linewidth(0.75));
clip((xmin,ymin)--(xmin,ymax)--(xmax,ymax)--(xmax,ymin)--cycle);

[/asy] The $y$-intercept of the graph is $(0,f(0)) = \left(0,-\frac53\right)$. To find the $x$-intercepts, we solve the equation $$\frac{(x-2)^2-9}{3} = 0,$$which yields $$(x-2)^2 = 9$$and thus $x=2\pm 3$. So, the $x$-intercepts are $(-1,0)$ and $(5,0)$.

The triangle whose vertices are $(-1,0),$ $(5,0),$ and $\left(0,-\frac 53\right)$ has base $6$ and height $\frac 53$, so its area is $$\frac 12\cdot 6\cdot \frac 53 = \boxed{5}.$$

