So we need to find n satisfying $2^n≡3\pmod{13}$. We consider the first few powers of 2 modulo 13, and look for a pattern.
\begin{align*}
2^1&≡2\pmod{13}\\
2^2&≡4\pmod{13}\\
2^3&≡8\pmod{13}\\
2^4&≡3\pmod{13}
\end{align*}
So $n=4$ is the first solution. The powers of 2 modulo 13 are cyclic with period 4, so all solutions of $2^n≡3\pmod{13}$ are $4\mid n+4m\iff 13\mid n-4m+4$. Thus $n\equiv 4\pmod{13}$.
You could also solve the problem more quickly by simply checking $3^5\equiv 243≡2\pmod{13}$. Now $2^n≡3\pmod{13}$ is the same as $3^{2(n-4)}≡2\pmod{13}$ so $13\mid 25(2n-8)-4\iff 13\mid 92n-131$ so $n\equiv 4\pmod{13}$.)</think> <answer> $3$ </answer>

